		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2014"></a><br><code>sle2014/keynote1</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2014</a> keynote:</span><br><i>From Language Engineering to Viewpoint Engineering</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/ColinAtkinson.html">Colin Atkinson</a></h2>
<ul><li>URL: <a href="https://www.sleconf.org/2014/Invited.html">https://www.sleconf.org/2014/Invited.html</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagM">T5H: Usability</span></a><ul><li> The keynote’s thesis is stakeholder-facing “viewpoints” that tailor information representation and interaction to user goals and capabilities.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It calls for foundations and (implicitly) tool support for engineering viewpoints (languages + context + interaction services) efficiently.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL">T4F: Visualisation</span></a><ul><li> View-oriented engineering foregrounds presentation/visualization choices (what information is shown/elided and how it is rendered).
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> “Viewpoints” are defined as augmentations over language definitions plus contextual and interaction layers—i.e., a structured composition of concerns.
</li></ul></li></ul>
